# Agentforce Lightning Types (Cursor Rule)

When the user is building, customizing, or debugging a custom Lightning Type intended for an Agentforce chat surface, follow this contract exactly. This is the **Apex-based** CLT pattern — required for Service Agent (Chat V2), Employee Agent (LEX assist panel), and Mobile.

## When to apply
- User mentions: "Lightning Type", "CLT", "agent chat UI", "Agentforce render", "custom output rendering".
- Files in `lightningTypes/**` or LWC `js-meta.xml` with target `lightning__AgentforceInput` / `lightning__AgentforceOutput`.

## When NOT to apply
- Object-based CLTs for Experience Builder / Prompt Builder / generic Einstein Agent actions (different schema rules).
- MIAW (non–Chat V2) deployments — CLTs are not supported there.
- Plain LWCs on record/app/home pages.

## File structure (must match)
```
lightningTypes/<typeName>/
  schema.json
  enhancedWebChat/         # Service Agent / Chat V2
    renderer.json
    editor.json            # only if collecting input
  lightningDesktopGenAi/   # Employee Agent in LEX
    renderer.json
  lightningMobileGenAi/    # Mobile
    renderer.json
```

API version: **64.0 or later**.

## Apex contract
- Top-level class only. **No inner classes.** Inner classes break schema introspection.
- Every class: `global` (not `public`/`private`).
- Every exposed field: `@AuraEnabled`.
- Every class: `@JsonAccess(serializable='always' deserializable='always')`.
- Supported types: primitives, sObjects, lists, `Map<String, ...>`, other user-defined `global` classes following the same rules.

```apex
@JsonAccess(serializable='always' deserializable='always')
global class MyTypeData {
    @AuraEnabled global String title;
    @AuraEnabled global List<String> tags;
}
```

## schema.json
```json
{
  "title": "My Type",
  "description": "...",
  "lightning:type": "@apexClass/c__MyTypeData"
}
```
- Always use the `c__` prefix for local org / new managed-package metadata. Use the package namespace prefix only when referencing existing managed metadata.

## renderer.json / editor.json
```json
{
  "componentOverrides": {
    "$": { "definition": "c/myComponent" }
  }
}
```
- `$` = top-level override (one LWC for the whole shape — typical for chat).
- For property-level overrides, use the property name as key and bind with `{!$attrs.PropertyName}`.

## LWC view contract
- `js-meta.xml` target: `lightning__AgentforceOutput` (renderer) or `lightning__AgentforceInput` (editor). `isExposed=true`.
- Receive data via `@api value` (shape mirrors the Apex class).
- Receive `@api readOnly` (Boolean).
- Send input back via `dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('valuechange', { detail: { value: <newShape> } }))`.

```js
import { api, LightningElement } from 'lwc';
export default class MyComponent extends LightningElement {
    _value;
    @api get value() { return this._value; }
    set value(v) { this._value = v || {}; }
    @api readOnly = false;
}
```

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<LightningComponentBundle xmlns="http://soap.sforce.com/2006/04/metadata">
    <apiVersion>64.0</apiVersion>
    <isExposed>true</isExposed>
    <targets><target>lightning__AgentforceOutput</target></targets>
</LightningComponentBundle>
```

## Wire-up checklist (org-side)
1. Agent action returns the Apex class (or Flow with output var typed `c__MyTypeData`). For input CLTs, the input variable's data type is `@apexClassType/c__MyFilterData` at the action-variable level.
2. Action settings:
   - **Show in conversation = ON**
   - **Output Rendering** parameter on the relevant output variable → select your CLT
   - **Input Rendering** parameter on the relevant input variable → select your input CLT (input only fires on Inquire/Confirm steps)
   - "Map to Variable" may show **"Unsupported Data Type"** when a CLT is selected — per docs, this is benign and can be ignored.
3. Permission set granting agent user access to the Apex class.
4. Service Agent only: ESD site CORS configured to my-domain.
5. Reload the agent page before retesting after changes.

## Multi-CLT pattern
A single agent action can wire two CLTs — one filter CLT on the input (with `editor.json` + input LWC, target `lightning__AgentforceInput`) and one response CLT on the output (with `renderer.json` + output LWC, target `lightning__AgentforceOutput`). Each is a separate `lightningTypes/` bundle.

When an input CLT exists but the planner asks for fields inline as text instead, tune the topic/subagent instructions to prefer the rendered form ("present the filter form rather than asking field by field").

## Testing
- Agent Builder preview does **not** render CLTs — don't rely on it.
- Test Service Agent via **Setup → Embedded Service Deployments → \[deployment\] → Test Enhanced Web Chat**.
- After any Apex shape change, **delete and recreate the agent action** — references go stale silently.

## Top gotchas (in order)
1. Missing `lightning__AgentforceInput`/`Output` target → component never renders, silent.
2. Apex class is `public` instead of `global` → fails in managed/namespaced contexts.
3. Missing `@JsonAccess` → silent serialization failure.
4. Input LWC ignored, agent goes straight to output → that action is an Inform step. Inputs only fire on **Inquire** or **Confirm** steps. Enable "Require user confirmation" or restructure the action.
5. Input form exists but agent asks fields as text → planner choosing text over form. Tune topic/subagent instructions to prefer the rendered form.
6. Apex shape changed after action was built → reload the agent page; if still stale, delete & recreate the action.
7. "Unsupported Data Type" on Map to Variable → benign per docs, ignore.
8. Service Agent silent load failure → ESD site missing CORS to my-domain.
9. Local class referenced as `MyTypeData` instead of `c__MyTypeData` in `schema.json`.

## Reference patterns

For 8 known-good shapes (carousel, item selector, add-to-cart, embedded form with conditional fields, file upload v1/v2, formatted URL, article cards, embedded screen flow), follow the catalog at `~/.claude/skills/agentforce-lightning-types/references/patterns.md` (or the project-level copy if synced). Each is a working unmanaged package — install and adapt rather than rebuilding.

A runnable starter (`HighlightCard` — title + description + image + URL) lives at `~/.claude/skills/agentforce-lightning-types/examples/highlightCard/`.
